What is special about the regenerative abilities of sea stars?

Sea stars are famous for their ability to regenerate limbs, and in some cases, entire bodies. They accomplish this by housing most or all of their vital organs in their arms. Some require the central body to be intact to regenerate, but a few species can grow an entirely new sea star just from a portion of a severed limb.

When sea stars are injured, they have the remarkable ability to regenerate.  They can regrow lost limbs and even regenerate entire missing arms.  In fact, there have been reports of regeneration in sea stars missing up to 75% of their bodies.  This ability to regenerate has been studied extensively in sea stars, and the findings are now being applied to other fields of biology.  For example, researchers are using sea star regeneration to help us understand the processes behind regeneration in mammals.

How do sea stars feed?

Most sea stars have the remarkable ability to consume prey outside their bodies. Using tiny, suction-cupped tube feet, they pry open clams or oysters, and their sack-like cardiac stomach emerges from their mouth and oozes inside the shell. The stomach then envelops the prey to digest it, and finally withdraws back into the body.

Sea stars are carnivores. They feed on a variety of invertebrates, including sea urchins, mollusks, bivalves, worms, and other echinoderms. Sea stars have tube feet that they use to move around and to manipulate prey. When they find food, they use their mouth parts to pull the prey into their mouth and then they use their stomachs to digest the food.

What is catastrophic molt in penguins?

Soon after the chicks fledge, parents will begin molting. Unlike some birds that shed a few feathers at a time, penguins lose all their feathers at once during a process called catastrophic molt. They condense this process to just a few weeks because they must fast during this time—they can’t hunt without their waterproof feathers.

The penguins shed their feathers completely, which is known as a catastrophic molt. The loss of feathers leaves the penguins unable to swim, and they must remain on land until their new feathers grow in. This is the time when they are most vulnerable to predators, and they are forced to huddle together for warmth and protection.

Commercial fishing in the Southern Ocean is also a significant concern, as it has reduced fish supply by about half in the Antarctic Peninsula. This forces many penguins to compete for food, and puts them in danger of getting accidentally captured by fishing nets.

What are the main threats to dolphins?

For centuries, people have hunted dolphins for their meat and blubber. Today, their main threat comes from being caught accidentally in commercial fishing nets. Dolphins must rise regularly to the surface to breathe—becoming entangled in nets prevents this, leading to drowning.

The greatest threats to dolphins and other marine mammals are human activity and habitat destruction. The main threats are:

- Capture and slaughter for food, clothing, entertainment, and so on.
- Pollution of the oceans, rivers, and lakes.
- Accidental capture in fishing nets.
- Habitat destruction and loss of food sources.
- The effects of climate change.

What are the threats to dolphins?

Habitat destruction, pollution, hunting, and accidental deaths in fishing nets are the greatest threats to dolphins.
How does climate change affect dolphins?

For marine dolphins, warming ocean temperatures because of climate change have caused some of their primary food sources to move into deeper, cooler water. Furthermore, marine heatwaves, also caused by climate change, appear to have a negative effect on dolphins' reproductive rates and ability to survive.

The effects of climate change on dolphins are becoming increasingly apparent. As sea levels rise and ocean temperatures increase, dolphins are forced to adapt to changing conditions, and in some cases, populations are threatened or even in danger of extinction.

One of the most significant impacts of climate change on dolphins is the disruption of their migration patterns. Dolphins rely on specific habitats for breeding, feeding, and resting. As these habitats become less hospitable due to changes in temperature, salinity, and other factors, dolphins must migrate to new areas to find suitable conditions.
What threats do freshwater dolphins face?
In addition to hunting and entanglement in fishing gear, freshwater dolphins face the additional threat of dams fragmenting and degrading habitat.

Freshwater dolphins are threatened by habitat loss, pollution, dams, and overfishing.

How do freshwater dolphins find food?

Freshwater dolphins use echolocation to find their prey. They emit clicks and listen for the echoes that bounce off objects. They can hear the echoes better than we can hear sounds, so they are able to detect the presence of fish, insects, and other prey even when it is hidden underwater.
